  "prompt": "How dangerous are corn snakes, and are they venomous?",
  "response": "Corn snakes (Pantherophis guttatus) are non-venomous constrictor snakes native to the southeastern United States. They are commonly kept as pets due to their docile nature and manageable size, typically growing to about 4 to 6 feet in length. \n\nCorn snakes are not dangerous to humans. Although they may bite if threatened or handled improperly, their bites are harmless and similar to that of a typical household pet's bite. They are beneficial for controlling rodent populations, making them important in their natural ecosystems.\n\nIn summary, corn snakes are not venomous and are generally considered safe for humans, making them popular as both pets and beneficial wild snakes.",
